but I would argue that you shouldn&#39;t.  That input format is really inappropriate.  If you have unstructured data like that, you should insist that the producer use a better format.  If you cannot change the producer, then you should use a different language to modify the data to make it more appropriate.  For example, your C code can simply be:

    /* Read integer data into an array. */
    #include &lt;stdio.h&gt;
    #include &lt;stdlib.h&gt;
    
    int
    main(int argc, char **argv)
    {
            unsigned rows, cols;
    
            if( argc != 3 ||
                    ( rows = strtol(argv[1], NULL, 10)) == 0 ||
                    ( cols = strtol(argv[2], NULL, 10)) == 0
            ) {
                    fputs(&quot;invalid parameters\n&quot;, stderr);
                    return EXIT_FAILURE;
            }
    
            int a[rows][cols];
    
            if(fread(a, sizeof **a, rows* cols, stdin) != rows * cols) {
                    fputs(&quot;Unexpected EOF\n&quot;, stderr);
                    return EXIT_FAILURE;
            }
    }

and given a text input file, you can use it with:

    perl -ane &#39;print pack(&quot;i*&quot;, @F)&#39; input | ./a.out ${N?} ${M?}

Note that this will now work with an input file in which all of the data is on one row, or if the data is structured incorrectly.  (eg, one row with 5 entries and another row with 3 entries could be read as a 2x4 matrix or a 4x2).  Whether or not this is a problem or a feature is in the eye of the beholder.  If it&#39;s a feature, nothing need be done.  If it&#39;s a problem, put the error checking in the filter (eg, the `perl`), not in the C code.  If you do want to check the format, you could emit a terminal character into the data stream at the end of each line (eg, `perl -lane &#39;print pack(&quot;i*&quot;, @F)&#39; input` to put a newline after each row) and then fread one row at a time, then do a getchar to make sure there is a `&#39;\n&#39;`, and then at the end do an getchar and ensure that you get EOF...but I really don&#39;t think it&#39;s worthwhile.

Note that in both of these examples, I&#39;ve put the size of the matrix as command line arguments.  This seems appropriate, since your code seems intended for interactive use.  If you want to read the parameters from the data stream, that is a fairly trivial change to make.  Just read from the stream instead of parsing the command line.

